<section xml:id="sec-linear-approximation">
  <title>Linear approximation</title>

  <objectives>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Use differentials to construct linear approximations near a point.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Interpret a function's linearization as its best local straight-line model.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Evaluate accuracy using concavity and basic error estimates.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </objectives>
  
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Introduction goes here.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        Approximation using differentials
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Linearization of a function at <m>x=a</m>:
        <me>
          L(x)=f(a)+f'(a)(x-a)
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Use second derivative for over/underestimate analysis
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              If <m>f''(a)>0</m>, then <m>f</m> is concave up around <m>a</m>, so <m>L(x)\lt L(a)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              If <m>f''(a)\lt 0</m>, then <m>f</m> is concave down around <m>a</m>, so <m>L(x)>L(a)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Absolute error: <m>\eps=|y-y\tsub{approx}|</m>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Relative error: <m>\eta=\dfrac{\eps}{|y|}</m>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        These can eventually get tied in with limits in Chapter 5.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</section>
